TPRS Quasi-Poisson Regression

Samuel Herold, Kayleigh Keller

This simulation looks at the effectiveness of varying degrees of freedom (up to 100) of Thin Plate Regression Splines as basis functions in a QuasiPoisson Regression to try to remove spatial confounding. The true b1 is 1, and is our target. Samples of size 1000 were taken 50 times. 4 experiments were ran with different density of the base gp surface and the confounding service (combinations of .1 and .25).

Trial 1

## [1] "X created using a spectral density of: 0.25. Confounder created using a spectral density of: 0.1."

Trial 2

## [1] "X created using a spectral density of: 0.1. Confounder created using a spectral density of: 0.1."

Trial 3

## [1] "X created using a spectral density of: 0.1. Confounder created using a spectral density of: 0.25."

Trial 4

## [1] "X created using a spectral density of: 0.25. Confounder created using a spectral density of: 0.25."

TPRSs appear to not be effective in quasi - poisson regression, although seem very slightly beneficial when the confounder has a higher c value/density than g. SD and SE increase together. b0 skyrocketed in 3/4 of situations.
